│ THOUGHT: Now I can see the core issue! The `matchSelectPattern` function    │
│ only handles standard ICMP predicates like `ICMP_SGT`, `ICMP_SGE`, etc.,    │
│ but it doesn't handle the `samesign` variants. The `samesign` predicate is  │
│ a special LLVM predicate that has different semantics and can produce       │
│ poison values. When the function encounters a `samesign` predicate, it      │
│ likely falls through to the default case and returns `SPF_UNKNOWN`, but     │
│ somewhere in the optimization pipeline, there's logic that incorrectly      │
│ assumes that if the first condition is true, then the second condition is   │
│ safe to evaluate.                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the original issue, the problem is that `(select (icmp samesign  │
│ sgt %In, -1), (icmp samesign eq %In, 1), false)` gets optimized to just     │
│ `(icmp samesign eq %In, 1)`. This optimization is incorrect because when    │
│ `%In = -2147483648` (0x80000000), the first condition `%c1` evaluates to    │
│ false (so the select returns false), but the second condition `%c2` would   │
│ be poison. The optimization removes the guard provided by the select.       │
│                                                                             │
│ The fix should be to prevent this optimization when dealing with `samesign` │
│ predicates. I need to find where the optimization that removes the select   │
│ is happening. Looking back at the InstCombineSelect.cpp file, I suspect the │
│ issue is in the logic that tries to simplify selects where one operand is a │
│ constant (false in this case).                                              │
│                                                                             │
│ Let me check if there's a specific optimization that removes the condition  │
│ when the false value is constant and the true value is another ICMP.        │
